You have pursued and slain many of the Barghests who haunt the Barrow-downs.
The folk of Bree-land hail your efforts to protect the roads from roving bandits.
You've proven a match for the rotten hatred the trees of the Old Forest hold for the two-footed folk of Middle Earth.
Who would ever have thought that Neeker-breekers could grow that big?
You have proven your mettle against the Orcs who have invaded northern Bree-land.
People may snicker, but how many of them have had to fight one of these giant bloodsuckers?
Spiders have become quite a threat of late in Bree-land, but your prowess against them is well known.
The wights of the Barrow-downs no longer hold any terror for you. Now you just find them deeply unsettling.
From whence came these slimy horrors that now plague the Lone-lands, no one knows, but now you have taken their measure.
The Lords of the gaunt-men have taken notice of your activities....
No matter how many goblins you kill, the Lone-lands just seems to become overrun with yet more of them.
Without your strength, it seems likely the Lone-lands would be overrun with Orcs by now.
The Lone-lands, too, are infested by these eight-legged horrors, each stronger than the last -- yet still they fall before you!
Along with the goblins, Wargs have come to the Lone-lands. They'll not have free run as long as you stand against them!

The goblins have retaken deep delvings carved in the hills of the North Downs, inhabiting them in great droves While they have learned to fear your name, you don't seem to have made much of a dent in their numbers.
Most of the residents of the Northdowns have been driven away by the orcish incursion, but those few who remain now herald your name as their saviour against these brutish invaders.
Long ago many princes and warriors of the Dunedain fell upon the Fields of Fornost - you cannot say if these horrors are them, but either way you've returned many of them to the peace of the grave.

Trolls - they are among the strongest and perhaps the least intelligent of the servants of the Enemy. Now it seems that these inhuman giants wander the Northdowns at will, or would, if you did not stand against them!
Anywhere goblins can be found, you'll likely encounter wargs. Thanks to your valiant efforts there are fewer of them in the North Downs however.

Legend has it that the Enemy spent long ages devising the great breed of Dragons that have bedeviled Middle Earth. Worms are among the lesser forms that were discarded along the way - but they are still deadly foes, and more common than their greater kin.
The bounders of the Shire look on you kindly for your help in dealing with the recent brigand troubles.
It has been long since the brood of Golfimbul endangered the folk of the Shire, but they will have to make it past you first.
The harvest-flies are more of a threat to the crops than to the folk of the Shire, but the farmers are thankful for your efforts to exterminate them.
You're not sure that this was the title you were looking for when you set out on the path of an adventurer...
Like so many places in Middle-earth, the Shire has seen a recent infestation of dangerous spiders, but they have learned to fear your sting!
Just as in olden days, wolves again threaten the Shire, but you have taught them a lesson they'll not soon forget.
The Dourhands have proven a sore thorn in the side of Durin's Folk, having lost the respect and trust of their kin.
Ancestral foes of Dwarf and Elf alike, goblins again challenge the lands of Ered Luin, but you stand ready to defy them.
Unlike the noble Eagles, the crooked hendrovail are used as spies for dark masters across many lands -- Ered Luin included.
Spiders have long lurked in all the dark corners of Middle-earth, but those of Ered Luin, at least, have reason to fear you.
Driven down from the frozen north, wolves are a constant challenge to all those who live in Ered Luin, but your prowess has proven their master.
These evil Men wield terrible powers granted them by their Dark Lord -- but such magic will avail them not as you pursue them into the deepest corners of their great strongholds in the north.

Numbering in the tens of thousands, Orcs have long formed the mainstay of the Enemy's armies. You long ago lost count of how many of these foul creatures have fallen before you - and yet their numbers seem undiminished.
The trolls of Angmar are the deadliest of all you have faced. Wielding arms and armour from the forges of the Enemy and possesed of a cruel cunning, even great heroes have fallen before their might.
The mighty Uruk form the elite forces of the armies of Angmar. Having defeated so many of their kind in battle, your name now commands a certain respect - and even deeper emnity - among their ranks.
The dreadful Wargs raised within the kennels of Angmar have known no other masters - until now. Still, it seems they are not about to let you pet them.

Angmar hosts a dread valley of spirits enthralled to the power of the Witch-King, and they do his bidding in his absence. There are few places in all Middle-Earth that inspire such dread as those halls - the Orcs and goblins give it wide breadth, while only the most fanatical of the Angmarim will enter to perform dark rites therein.
Mishaphen half-children of the great Dragons of old, the Worms of Angmar possess a fair portion of their elder brood's power and cunning. Yet you have overcome their power and proven their match.
You've heard that the giants sometimes breed the largest bears as pets - and that wouldn't surprise you. They grow them big here in the Misty Mountains - really big.

You'd thought these great creatures must be legend and myth when you were told stories of them by your parents. Not any more. Their strength is as great as their size, and their bravery that of a creature that knows it is unmatched. Nevertheless, the valour of you and your companions has laid many of these titans low in battle.

The Snow-beasts that inhabit the Misty Mountains are odd creatures. You'd only heard vague tales of them before you came there, and most people would consider them myths, but you've fought enough of them to be quite sure they are real.
Where they may have come from is anyone's guess. Perhaps the Enemy found them far in the distant North somewhere, beyond the boundaries of Man or Elf.

As if the biting cold in the Misty Mountains wasn't bad enough, it seems to have given rise to a particularly unpleasant breed of troll. These creatures thrive in the ice and frost, and they lurk here waiting to crush and devour any traveller unlucky enough to stumble upon them.

Where there are goblins there are Wargs, and the Misty Mountains are no exception. Tempered by the deadly cold and harsh conditions, these Wargs have become particularly vicious and deadly but you've found them to be passable opponents at best.

It is said that worms have long lived in the far north, among the desolate and frozen wastes. Alas, it seems only natural then that as the gates of Angmar have been laid open that they should have unleashed many of the creatures into the frozen peaks of the Misty Mountains, there to breed and to terrorize any who attempt the dangerous passage.
And here you'd thought nothing could be worse than the bugs in Midgewater. These many legged horrors have changed your mind on the matter, but not stopped your battle to protect Middle Earth.
It took more than a flyswatter to bring down so many of these prodigious foes - a feat for which you are rightly renowned.
These lands weren't named the Trollshaws without good reason. You've certainly found no shortage of the brutes to test your mettle against!
Even the Elves of Rivendell claim not to know whence the horrid wights infesting the Trollshaws came from. Nevertheless you have forced many of them back into the earth from which they escaped.

The wolves that inhabit the Trollshaws are among the most wild and powerful of that breed. Serving neither Man nor Goblin, these wolves prey upon any foolish enough to venture into their territory - save for you.

Where could so many of these terrible beasts have been hidden away? The wastes of the far North, or buried beneath the Gates of Angmar? It doesn't really matter where they came from, so long as you strive to drive them from the lands of Middle Earth.

You grew up in Bree-land, once part of the North Kingdom of Arnor, once ruled by Elendil the Tall as High King of Middle-earth, and later by his elder son Isildur. Now it is but a simple, rustic land, and the North Kingdom is no more.
You come from the Dale-lands in the north-east of Middle-earth, beneath the Lonely Mountain, where Bard the Bowman slew the dragon Smaug and fought in the Battle of Five Armies.
You hail from the land of Gondor, the South Kingdom once ruled conjointly by the sons of Elendil, Isildur and Anárion, ever-watchful against the looming threat of Mordor.
You are one of the Horse-lords of the Riddermark, the realm granted to Eorl the Young by Cirion, Steward of Gondor, currently ruled by Théoden, son of Thengel.
Lovers of trees and woodlands, the Fallohides were the first hobbits to come to the Shire. They generally tend to be fairer of skin and hair, as well as taller and more slender.
The Harfoots are the most prodigious hole-dwellers and were the first to cross west into Eriador. They generally tend to be browner of skin than the other kindreds, as well as smaller and shorter.

The Stoors were the last of the hobbit kindreds to come to the Shire, settling at last in the eastern marshlands of the Shire. The generally tend to be heavier and broader of build than the other kindreds.
You come from the Iron Hills, settled by dwarves as a refuge from the Cold-drakes, and whence came Dáin Ironfoot, King under the Mountain, kinsman of the great Thorin Oakenshield.
You hail from Erebor, the Lonely Mountain, where Smaug the Golden made his lair until Thorin Oakenshield reclaimed it for his people. There does Dáin Ironfoot now rule as King under the Mountain.

Your home is in Ered Luin, the Blue Mountains, where there had once been two great dwarf-kingdoms and where the kinsmen of Thráin and his son Thorin Oakenshield lived in exile after Smaug drove them from the Lonely Mountain.

You are from Ered Mithrin, the Grey Mountains, the chief of which is Mount Gundabad, from whence came Durin the Deathless, first Father of the Dwarves. Your kindred returned to the Mountains after the Dragons perished.

You are from the south-western halls of Ered Nimrais, the White Mountains in the south bordering the lands of Andrast. Though your kingdom lies far from the central mountains where Men once dwelt, the rumour of the Oathbreakers has given your realm an ill name.

You hail from Lindon, the green lands of the Elves between Ered Luin and the Sea, where Gil-galad, the last great Elf-king, once ruled. Círdan the Shipwright now rules there from Mithlond, the Grey Havens.
You come from Lothlórien, the fabled golden woods whose Elves dwell high in the mallorn-trees and are ruled by Celeborn, wisest of the Eldar of Middle-earth, and the Lady Galadriel.

You are a Wood-elf of Mirkwood, once called Greenwood the Great, where King Thranduil keeps watch against the growing darkness of Dol Guldur, former stronghold of Sauron in his guise as the Necromancer.
You hail from Imladris, called Rivendell by Men, built by Elrond Halfelven as a refuge for the Elves of Eregion as they fled destruction at the hands of Sauron.
You are of the Nandor of Edhellond, the great Elf-haven in the south built by Amroth at the Mouths of Anduin.

Mordirith, leader of Angmar in the stead of the Witch King, looks upon you as a trusted servant. His favour will earn you greater favour with the Lugburz!
You have defeated the captains of Ringdyr.
You have defeated the captains of Tol Ascarnen.
You have defeated the captains of the Towers.
You've hunted down a number of these annoying little backstabbers and shown them what it means to oppose the will of Angmar.
Those who would steal from the lords of Angmar will die by the sword, and at your hands many of them have.
Never trust a thief. For that matter, don't trust anyone.
Burglars can run, but they cannot hide from you. You've killed a great many of these filthy little sneaks in your time.
Tricksy and false? Hah! You've seen how 'tricksy' Burglars are when they are writhing in pain as you prepare to strike the killing blow. It's hardly even a sporting challenge any more.
These fools would lead the forces of Men? Then let them lead from the grave!
Rally their allies to them as they might, you've cut through and killed many of these banner-waving cretins.
The banners make them easy to spot on the battlefield, and ripe for the killing as you and your hordes fall upon them from the darkness.
Without their leaders, the forces of Men often fall to panic and cowardly flight. You have excelled at extinguishing these little sparks of false 'hope' upon the field of battle.

Few things warm your dark heart quite like the crestfallen look upon the faces of your enemies as yet another of their Lords falls in battle before you.
It is a sight you have enjoyed so very often...
These self-righteous crusaders have often fallen before your own unheralded strength.
Champions respect strength above all else - a trait which you have displayed in plenty as you've hewed through their ranks.

He who lives by the sword had best expect to die by it.
You make a point of giving these fool Champions every opportunity to do so at your hands.

What good is courage to one who lies, broken and bleeding beneath your feet? Who knows?
Who cares.
Hah! For self-styled 'Heroes', these Champions fall like wheat before the scythe of your power. They are no match for you, nor shall they ever be!

These self-styled Guardians stand between you and the towns and villages of the West, which lie ripe for the plucking.
The more of them you kill, the sooner you can start the looting.
Why would these iron-hided scum stand between you and the weak? You'll never understand it - but you've proven they can be swept aside all the same.
Though they carry great shields and clothe themselves in burnished steel, no-one may stand before the power of Angmar and live. You've seen to that.

Defenders of the Weak indeed! Who then shall defend these supposed Guardians from you, eh?
No-one, that's who...

Those who stand before the tide are doomed to drown in its fury.
You charge in the vanguard of the endless armies of Angmar and crush those Guardians who dare to stand with armies of the West, without mercy or hesitation.
These vicious opponents would attempt to sap the strength of Angmar from afar, you've found it best to take the battle to them in person.
You've killed your share of the enemy's scouts. They would do better to cower behind their allies in battle, but then what's the sport in that?
With neither shield or armour, Hunters make for easy prey upon the battlefield. Sure the arrows sting a bit, but pain is the mark of a true warrior.
Ah, the joy when the tables are turned and the Hunter becomes the Hunted! So many of these miscreants have fallen before you now that you've nearly lost count.

Bows may be fearsome weapons in skilled hands, but they cannot protect their wielders from the swift and certain death that you bring upon them in battle. They are just more kindling for the bonfires of Angmar!
The Wise? feh! The truly Wise need understand only power. Those who profess wisdom in knowledge often die at your hands.
No magic can protect these bookworms from your wrath. If they understood even a fraction of the power commanded by the Lords of Angmar, they would cower in abject surrender before death.
What's so special about a staff? Just another stick to be broken - right before you break the one who wields it, as you have so often before.
What good are old books and a fine pointy hat when you've got three feet of steel protruding from your gut? None at all! You've proved the wisdom of that statement often enough.

No overblown scribe can challenge you on the battlefield.
Scrolls, books, staves, robes - all shall burn in the bonfires of Angmar!

What kind of fool comes to the battlefield to sing rather than fight?
A dead fool.
The songs of the West sound far more pleasing to your ears when they gurgle forth from a slit throat.
The discordant snapping of strings, the splintering of wood, and the screams of the dying are all the music needed to accompany your rampage.

The leaderless scum of the West are said to believe that the world was born from a song.
Perhaps, perhaps not, but the last music they shall hear before their fall shall be the war-drums of Angmar!

In the wake of your passage, the fields of battle take on an unnatural stillness broken only by the moans of the dying.
No songs escape from the lips of the fallen, for no life remains to utter them.
You have assisted Gundzor earning the rank of drudge.
You have continued to assist Gundzor earning the rank of flunky.
You have become known to Gundzor as more than a servant; you are a defender of his post in the Grimwood.
You have assisted Bûrzgoth and earned the title of his thrall.
You have continued to assist Bûrzgoth and earned the right to be his toady.
You have become known to Bûrzgoth as one who will do as he says, when he says.
You have assisted the master of Lugazag and earned the right to be at his beck and call.
You have continued to assist the master of Lugazag and firmed your position as his servant.
You have become known to Tharbil as more than a servant; you are a defender of his post at Lugazag.
You have assisted the master of Tirith Rhaw and earned station as his servant.
You have earned greater favour of the master of Tirith Rhaw and can now be named a hound. A loyal dog.
You have become known to Barashish as more than a servant; you are a defender of his post at Tirith Rhaw.
You have assisted the master of Tol Ascarnen and earned the right to be called a truckler.
You have continued to assist Trintrû earning the right to be called his lickspittle.
None question your devotion to Trintrû, thus you are called his sycophant.
Helping Holly Hornblower has honoured her and hastened hungry hobbits into happy hobbits.
For your help to the Quick Post, Postmaster Proudfoot has declared you an official postman.
With your coming sounds the trump of Doom, for by your hand have many of the warriors of the Free People fallen bested by your might.
Your legend has grown so much amongst the Elves that you are now a true villain. They know only to run from you when you near them!
Valour crumbles when you near. The Dwarves' courage spills from them as easily as their innards when you are about. The death delivered by your hands sunders hope.
Men quake at the mention of your name, as your blade bites deeply into their flesh.
Your continued destruction of the little folk drives a spike of fear into their hearts.
Light ebbs in your presence. Strength leaves the enemy as the darkness you bring clouds their hope and drives dread into their hearts.
Your name is known amongst the Elves. It is used to strike fear into the hearts of the young.
When Angmar's Army moves beneath the world to face the Dwarves in their mountain homes, perhaps you shall be the one to lead it. You have proven yourself most adept at slaying these vermin!
You are an officer within a Tribe.
Without compassion or care you flay flesh from the little folk and have become one of the most adept at culling their number from the world.
You are the founder of a Tribe.
You are a herald of the Dark Lord. You have culled countless numbers from the field of battle and none escape your grasp.
Dwarves quake before you! You cleave and heave their bodies aside by the hundred!
You are a leader within a Tribe.
You are the founder of a Tribe.
You are known as the Bane of the West, for none of their warriors can stand against you, and windrows of their fallen lie heaped in your wake.
Continued efforts against the Dwarves earn you great glory. You are seen as their bane by others in Angmar's ranks.
You are an officer within a Tribe.
Slaughtering the little folk has earned you a mark of savagery against their kind.
You are an officer within a Tribe.
Your victories against the bearded folk beneath the mountain brand you their foe.
Countless deaths by your hand tarnish Men. Their honour breaks as easily as their wills when you stride onto the fields of battle.
Men fear you. There are none who do not know your name in battle and all Men quake in terror at its mention.
Your blade has tasted the flesh of many Elves and it desires the blood of more.
You are a leader within a Tribe.
Cleaving through the ranks of Men drives you to near frenzy. You are known for slaughter and tearing flesh from Men.
You are a grunt within a Tribe.
You are a grunt within a Tribe.
You are known as a tormenter of the Free People.
Your blade drinks the blood of Man freely. There are few who would stand against you!
Your rank, name, and surname, sans title.
You are a leader within a Tribe.
You are the founder of a Tribe.
You are a leader within a Tribe.
You are a grunt within a Tribe.
You are an officer within a Tribe.
The field of battle serves as a garden from which you reap the heads of the fallen. You are a true harvester of sorrow.
Grace falters when you draw close. There are none amongst the Elves who will stand before you. The destruction wrought by your hand has crippled grace.
There are no little folk who dare stand before you. Your prowess over them is known to all as you tear through them with impunity.
You are the founder of a Tribe.
You are a grunt within a Tribe.
Angmar casts a favouring eye upon you, you are known as an elite amongst their number. A hound of Mordirith; a Black Dog!
All who draw breath and hold ties to the Elven Folk fear your blade. You drive their number from the fields of battle.
Your domination over the little folk is absolute. The blood spilled by your hands has soiled the innocence these creatures once enjoyed.
You are now indoctrinated to Angmar's Army!
You have completed the first volume of the Shadows of Angmar.
You have slain a great many of the tomb-robbers that threaten the burial places of the Kings of Annúminas.
Some secret lies hidden within the glimmering lights that haunt the fields of Evendim -- it seems on the tip of your tongue, but ever eludes you….
The savage Gauredain have learned to respect your strength, and perhaps even fear you -- if they ever allowed themselves to show fear in battle.
The Hill-giants inhabiting the hills above Evendim have come to call you their foe, and they plan for the day when they might have their vengeance upon you.
The goblins and the strange little boggarts that creep about the fringes of Evendim have learned to give you wide berth if they value their lives at all.

Thus far you have laid waste to the deadly Kergrim and have not yet fallen prey to their vicious claws.
Should the day come when you make a mistake in battle against them, not even your bones will be left for others to mourn.
The salamanders of Evendim have tried time and again to destroy you, to no avail as their fire flickers and dims before your might.
For completing the Tavern League's grueling test, you are now a true member
For winning the Hobnanigan's match during Summerdays as a member of the Steel Beaks team.
For winning the Hobnanigan's match during Summerdays as a member of the Flying Feathers team.
Storvâgûn's treachery, and his life, have been ended.
Those who sold their loyalty for riches have tasted the vengeance of the righteous.
Less ice-hatchlings now and less drakes later, a victory for the Free Peoples!
Being a true hero requires more then strength of arms and will.
Even the reborn dragon Thorog has fallen before you.
Many worked together to bring this victory, but you stand above the rest, a true hero.
The Servants Four are no more, but you prevail.
The Corcur of Helegrod know your name, but speak it in frightened whispers.
Angmar now fears your name and the names of your allies.
You have harvested the evil venom of Zaudru's brood to serve the greater good.
Many of the brood of Zaudru have fallen to your might.
Not even the foul Zaudru can stand before you.
The evil spider Gwigon has made its lair amongst the twisting barrow of Haudh Iarchith and there his brood multiplies, save for your efforts to exterminate them.
So many corpses have clawed up from their graves amongst the labyrinthine barrows of Haudh Iarchith, that it seems you have more need of a shovel than a sword.

A number of vicious and corrupt beasts reside within the ruins of Sarnúr, and they have fallen under the sway of the Dourhands and their allies.
Your will and strength has mastered these vermin nevertheless.
The Dourhand brigands have established a stronghold within the ancient ruins of Sarnúr, but your battles against them have thinned their numbers and weakened their hold on it.
Amongst the rotting horror of Haudh Iarchith, a gathering of corrupt and evil entities holds sway over a dark court - or at least, they did, before you found and destroyed them.
Many fallen spirits roam the dark tunnels of Haudh Iarchith, yet if there is anything that they might fear amongst the living, it is you.

An alliance of enemies plots against Ered Luin from within the ancient ruins of Sarnúr, as the traitorous Dourhand seek to bring an array of forces to bear against their hated cousins the Longbeards - luckily, your excursions into the ruins have resulted in the deaths of many of their leaders.

It seems that the trolls inhabiting Sarnúr are of a particularly dim-witted - if brutal - strain.
Under the guidance of the Dourhands however, they cannot be ignored - though how long their allegience might last is uncertain…
You ate the cheese even after observing all of the warning signs. This makes you especially unwise.
There are many deep secrets in Middle Earth, but you have great insight into what part the chickens play in it all.

Let it be known to all Men, Elves, Dwarves, and Hobbits (hereinafter 'the Free Peoples') that Will Tuffin, being of suitable age and discretion and found within the boundaries of the Shire, has been served with process in accordance with applicable law and with all due diligence by the bearer of this title.
